2) Evaluation of the two candidates in light of that preference:
- Frontiers is labeled Classic Rock; Album-Oriented Rock (AOR). AOR by definition emphasizes cohesive full-album sequencing, extended arrangements and production intended to be heard as an album — characteristics that play to the strengths of listening to physical CDs as complete works. Frontiers (the well-known Journey album) also contains major, well-produced tracks ("Separate Ways," "Faithfully") that are emblematic of an album crafted for strong album-side listening and high-fidelity reproduction.
- Yes I Am is labeled Pop; Adult Alternative. Pop and adult-alternative releases often emphasize radio singles and individual tracks; while they can be excellent, their structure and production are typically more single-focused than deliberately album-oriented.
3) Reason for my choice and rejection of the other:
Because my only stated preference is that I enjoy listening to CDs, I prioritized which candidate best rewards dedicated album listening. "Frontiers" is explicitly AOR — a genre that aligns directly with the CD-listening experience (cohesive sequencing, extended instrumental passages, and production choices that benefit from listening to the whole disc). That makes it the better match for someone valuing the CD format itself. I therefore choose Frontiers.
I reject "Yes I Am" not because it is inferior musically, but because its Pop/Adult Alternative orientation is less aligned with the album-as-a-whole listening experience emphasized by CD enthusiasts. Given no explicit genre preference in my introduction, choosing the record that most directly matches the activity I did state I enjoy (listening to CDs as complete albums) is the most fact-based and appropriate decision.

