- Rejected (Tapestry) because although it is beautifully intimate and dynamic, it is explicitly piano‑forward and designed as a cohesive album experience. That structure and timbral focus point away from the singles‑first, punchy pop/new‑wave values I favor: there’s unlikely to be the controlled, punchy low end, snapped percussion and razor‑sharp transients I prefer, and its minimal processing/natural ambience risks slipping into the “mellow acoustic” territory I critiqued when it lacks rhythmic drive. Tapestry’s strengths (piano intimacy, room ambience, full‑album reward) are also the reasons it diverges from my priorities: I prioritize concise, rhythmically driven, well‑punched pop mixes that put the lead vocal front and keep momentum—Candidate 1 better matches that balance.

